segments.text: AB, AB, 1, 2, 3, testing, AB.
DE, DE, DE, testing, testing.
My voice is not very good.
This is July 13th.
We're in room 207 of the Evans Library, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Jane Thompson.
colleague a long time ago.
I have the pleasure of recording her memories of being here on the staff a long, long time.
Describe growing up and your mother's work here.
I actually feel like I grew up on A&M campus because I frequented often when my mother had to work on Saturdays.
I came out and worked or played or whatever was available for quite a long time.

I have some fond memories of those days when I used to play in the administration building, like it was my home, my grand palace, and roller skate through the academic building where the wooden floors were, where the post office was.
There were wooden floors, and the roar of those roller skates was wonderful.
But I felt like A&M was really my home.
More than Bryan, Texas.
It's been good to me.
Let's see.
Let me.
There were not, in those years, were there any classes in the first floor of the academic?
Or was it pretty well all administration?
It had some classes, unfortunately.
Perhaps not Saturday classes, but there were classes, classrooms there.
And I remember the rotunda had a big glass case that had an owl in it.
in the middle, and that was a big feature to go and show everybody when they visited.
Let's see, your mom's task in those days, what was she doing?
My mother worked in several different places.
The one I remember the most was academic, student activities, excuse me.
student activities where I got to meet all the good looking officers of the Corps that came in to get their checks and visit and all their plans were made there.
So I remember some of those very well.
That pretty much sums up what I can, well, no.
I worked, I mean, when I was in junior high school,
we were recruited to come to the campus for the stadium for the film, We've Never Been Licked.
Talk about that.
Describe it.
They gave us a sack lunch, and we were bussed out to the campus.
They gave us a sack lunch, and we got to sit in the stands while they filmed the football scenes of that movie.
That's all I know about it.
That's pretty much all there was.
Do you remember seeing Robert Mitchum or any of the other stars?
We got to see the stars.
It was just a day away from school and we had fun doing it.
But that goes way back.
I used to work in the summers for Ray Perryman for the registrar's office when they were testing freshmen.
That was quite several days of testing of the freshmen coming in so they could evaluate their curriculum.
And what kind of work were you doing?
Oh, we were handing out the test papers and picking them up and whatever had to be done, monitoring them.
But Mr. Perriman was a dear man.

And in the beginning, he used to call on me over the loudspeaker at Speesa Hall because my name was the only name he could remember of all the students that worked for him, or all the summer students, because he was familiar with my mother.
So I got to work special for Mr. Perriman and worked for him in the summers later until I went to college.
Now, did he report to Mr. Heaton?
Yes.
He was, I think, assistant registrar.
But he did the statistical work for the registrar's office.
Would this have been an all-day Saturday job?
Yes.
It was all day.
Do you remember what the pay was?
Oh, no.
I have no idea.
We did get paid, though.
And in those years, when your mom came to the campus, did she come in her own car or ride with somebody?
They usually shared a ride with...
However, when my mother first worked for the university, before I was born, before she was married, she used to ride to the campus in the trolley from Bryan.
She lived in a boarding house in Bryan, and she got the trolley to work.
And...
Okay, then you're doing that.
You finished high school.
Finished high school, and I went to college at Sam Houston, and during the second summer term, I came down with infectious mononucleosis and had to drop out of school, and
ended up getting married the following February, so, to my biology professor.
So that pretty much ended my college career.
And then come back to Bryan when?
I mean, back to Bryan College Station when?
I came back to Bryan College Station in 1964.
And it was my idea, of course, to get a job on the campus, which is where I felt at home.
And my mother had told me there was a job opening in the office of the graduate college.
And she felt like at that time that it was beginning to grow, the graduate programs were going to grow.
And she thought that might be a good place for me to work or start to work.
And I interviewed there, got the job, and I stayed there for 25 years.
Describe the interview as well as you remember it.
Oh, Ms. Watson, Ms. Doris Watson.
Bless her heart, she was the typical administrative old maid secretary, if you want to call it that.
Bless her heart.
She wore glasses on the end of her nose.
And of course, she knew my mother too, and I have to say that helped me a great deal because I think they respected her and they treated me with respect.
So she did hire me.
I had not worked in an office all those years I was married, and I had to essentially start all over again.
But it was interesting work.
As far as you knew when you went to work, what were your duties going to be?
More or less, I was a receptionist, so it was perfectly harmless, almost.
I had to answer the phone and write on people and mail out.
And of course, we typed.
To the graduating doctorate students, we typed original letters to each student.
They had to be perfect.
So I had a lot of practice typing letters.
That was before the... What kind of machine were you using then to type those letters?
It was an electric machine.
It was?
Oh, okay.
Yeah, it was the first ones.
But you still had to erase typographical letters?
Oh, we had to, yes.

fact we weren't allowed to erase unless they just positively couldn't see it but she inspected each and every letter which she should have but I enjoyed working there and when I first remember working there I think we had all of four filing cabinets that the graduate applications were filed and I think in
89 when I retired, there were at least, oh, there had to be a hundred file cabinets, active and inactive students.
Describe what offices, when you went to work, describe what offices, what officials were in the Koch building.
The president was just across the hall, and the academic vice president for research, I believe, was with him.
I've been trying to think of his name.
I can't right now.
But that was pretty much all.
The registrar's office was in one side of Coke Billy.
The fiscal office was on the other, which for graduate programs was perfect because we could run down there and do whatever we needed to do with no problems.
That was an ideal situation.
And the registrar was down?
It was in the Coke Billy.
On the first floor.
On the first floor.
The fiscal office had one half and the registrar had the other half.
So it was a nice situation.
Describe those people that Earl Rutter was the president.
Describe Earl Rutter from your point of view.
I had very little contact with President Rutter, but I know that we had a great deal of respect for him and thought that he was a great leader, which we needed.
And he absolutely, when I was working for Dr. Coons, he let us do what we had to do without any interference at all.
And President Rutter's primary secretary was who?
Was Nelda Rowell.
And now Nelda Green.
Nelda Green.
Describe her as... Oh, a lovely, lovely lady, and she still is and always will be.
A really special person.
I was friends with all of the administrative secretaries on the campus, the secretaries to the deans, because we belonged to the National Secretary Association.
We had Bosses Night and all the good things.
We got very close.
We knew we could depend on each other, and we did, from time to time, call and ask for...
Can you do this?
Or will you tell me that?
So we worked very well together, and we had a lot of respect for each other.
I'm not going to ask you the negative now.
Among those key secretaries, who were your favorites, your closest colleagues?
I'd have to think about that.
Because I really, in the graduate office, we worked with all the deans.
So I really, I suppose Nelda was my favorite top secretary.
But Margaret Coleman in the engineering, wonderful person.
Amadele Backus in veterinary medicine.
I can't think of... And in that era there were only the deans of arts and sciences, agriculture, engineering, and veterinary medicine.
Peggy Ritchie of course is one of my favorite people and we shared an office at one time.
She worked for one of the deans and we
in the Koch building.
She was part of the office, so I got to know her very well, and she is a special person to me, too.
I do want to mention one of the jobs I had in the early years in the graduate office.
We had to take in all the thesis and dissertations over the desk.
We had to check them.
We had to count the pages.
We had to measure the margins.
Now, one of the only jobs I ever complained about that I can remember is checking thesis and dissertations.
I would do anything but have to do that.

So they gave me the job of when they came back from the bindery and they could submit as many copies as they wanted to pay six dollars for, I think it was, they could submit ten copies if they wanted to, but I had to
ship all those extra copies out to wherever they were.
So that was my penalty for not checking these dissertations.
As far as you know, whose idea was it to check those details?
Was that Dean Kunze's?
No, that went way back before Dean Kunze.
Dean Kunze is the one that wanted the thesis clerk in the library.
Thank goodness for that.
Now you went to work in what year?
All right.
Now Kunze was not yet the graduate.
No, he was not, and I'm sorry, I can't remember what year he came in, but see, Barczak was the associate dean, and then when they made a dean, they put Dean Kunze in as dean.
There was never another dean.
Wayne Hall was the vice president for academic affairs and...
The graduate college, yeah.
Describe Wayne Hall.
A quiet, very mannerly man.
Mrs. Watson did not let us have much communication with Dr. Hall.
She protected him very well, but he was always very nice.
Actually, I had just almost nothing to do with him.
What kind of hours did he work?
I have no idea, because we were segregated so from him that I didn't see him come in and I didn't see him leave.
We were in one half of that office, do you remember?
And he was in the other half.

And the only way the deans could see him, or associate deans, assistant deans, would sneak around the back of that office in the Koch building through the back side of it that was away from Mrs. Watson.
As far as you were aware,
Earl Rudder was a key decision maker.
Who else were key decision makers at A&M then?
Do you have any?
No, I'm sorry, I can't.

My world was the graduate office and I think the deans had a great deal of input to whatever was, it wasn't quite as complicated as it is now because there was the, the structure was a lot simpler then.
So the deans had a lot of input into what.
And normally your working hours were?
Eight to five.
But didn't you sometimes work?
Oh, well, as I went up the ladder in the office, my hours got longer and longer, but it was something I enjoyed doing.
The only problem is I had to certify graduating students' degrees three times a year every year, along with everything else that I had to do, and that got to be quite difficult.
Tiresome, to say the least.
Do you remember any crisis events about somebody doing something at the last minute?
Oh, we always had that.
That was pretty normal.
But I can remember when we had to submit a signed list of graduating students by a deadline, so many copies.
And in those days, the only copier we had was the mimeograph.
And the only mimeograph machine we had was in the president's office.
So we had to troop over there, and I was never one that was good at mimeographing.
It just never seemed to go right for me.
But anyway, we finally got a multilift operator in the fiscal office, and he used to run my list for me at the last minute.
But that was my most trauma.
We had those deadlines to meet.
Do you remember any time when, if anybody, a regent or a administrator or a parent tried to get y'all to make an exception to the rule?
No.
I truthfully cannot remember anything like that.
Especially when Dr. Kunze is dean, everything was completely above board.
he would have been the last person to ever let anything happen that he might embarrass himself or the college or anybody.
So we did the best job we could to make it as, I'm not saying that we didn't make mistakes occasionally.
I did graduate somebody who wasn't cleared one time.
But that was purely a clerical error.
This is an editorial note to the typist and to be identified as an editorial note.
I was invited to join this staff as assistant dean of the graduate school or assistant graduate dean or whatever it might be.
R.W.
Bill Barzak from the English department was the associate dean and Wayne Hall was vice president and graduate dean.
Then after a year or so,

Bill Barzac told me that he was going to go back to the English department, that he thought that Vice President Hall might ask me about moving up, and he did, ask me if I was interested, but it would be a full-time task, and I had been doing half-time and teaching and enjoyed that, and he said, no, it would have to be full-time, and I told him, well, I probably then would not be interested, but I also asked him,
how long might it be before they selected a graduate dean?
And he said that he thought that would probably be done within a year.
I then paused and asked him, would anyone from the liberal arts area have any chance to be considered?
He smiled and then said very confidently, we've already decided it's going to be someone from agriculture.
So I told him, no, I'd go on back, but I would stay to help that person get started.
And then so I worked with Dean George Kunze for a year and enjoyed that and found him to be a splendid person to work with.
Okay, end of note.
When Dr. Kunze came in, do you remember how he organized the
Did you become the senior person?
No.
He had to use Mrs. Watson.
So, she still was the supervisor of all of the support staff for graduate and academic VP.
Eventually, I mean it didn't take long that he couldn't live with that situation, so I did become his secretary.
but it was a little bit after that.
Make believe I've never seen George Kunze.
Describe him physically, his appearance.
George Kunze, I believe, probably came from the same part of Germany as the Pope.
in Italy.
They're built, they look the same build, same features almost as the pope in Italy.
Always pleasant man.
He would hit the door in the morning with his sack lunch heading for the refrigerator and speak to everybody in the office good morning.
I didn't realize how important that was until he was gone and nobody ever did it again.
But he was just that kind of man.
And when something went wrong, he absolutely dropped everything.
He sat there like he had the rest of the day to spend with you and you would talk about it.
I didn't really appreciate him until he was gone as much as I should have.
But there's not many like that.
Did you learn any pet peeves that he had?
Was there anything that he really didn't want anybody to do?
Oh, yes.

The main thing was we were in the Koch building on the second floor, had a lovely lounge outside between the offices, and he did not want the girls sitting out there doing handwork or anything like that.
He felt like anybody visiting the university would think that that was foolish, wasting time.
So the girls, they just didn't even try.
But he didn't want anybody reading at their desk, and he didn't want anybody sitting looking like they had nothing to do.
Of course, we never did have that freedom.
And in that era, the support staff never smoked.
Oh, no.
No, no.
We never had any smoking in our office.
Never even came up.
And what was appropriate dress?
Well, appropriate dress in the beginning was just your nice looking clothes like you would wear to church, perhaps.
Hose, of course, always.

But then there came a time when they were talking about pantsuits, so everybody wanted, that was the latest thing, and so we had a meeting, and he agreed that we could wear pantsuits if they were coordinated, and of course that was what everybody was wearing, and that was the most liberal thing we did.
How did y'all plan that meeting to bring that up?
Well, it just takes two or three girls.
The office wasn't that large at that time, so there weren't that many people in there, as you well know.
So it just took a couple of us to go to him, and he was open for suggestions.
He was always willing to listen.
He didn't always agree with us, but he was willing to listen.
I do want to say one thing I remember especially during those times was when you would come in the middle of the office and do your radio impersonations.
And Mrs. Watson glaring at you with her glasses.
But we enjoyed that so much and had such fun laughing about it.
And do you remember any great crises, big problems that... We had a lot of crises, but they were just taken care of as a matter of
I don't think we ever had anything get out of hand that I can remember.
Now this was the time when women were first attending.
Do you remember any problems that the graduate college had over co-education or racial integration?
No.
We really had, we actually just dealt with everybody the same.
I must say that I felt a little uneasy when the Iran crisis and those times when we had so many Iranian students.
And I just simply wasn't sure what would happen when you walk up to the window and be talking to someone.
And also mail bombs were a hot issue then.
But we didn't talk about it.
We didn't dwell on it.
We just handled things as we always had and tried not to make it an issue.
Where did you and your

colleagues where did y'all eat lunch in that era in the office usually we have a microwave we had when we moved over to the Teague building we had our refrigerator we shared a kitchen area with the Xerox with the College of Medicine so we had the lap of luxury there we had a microwave and we had a refrigerator and
We really just didn't go out a lot unless someone had to go home.
But eating out was not, maybe on Friday we would go out and eat together somewhere.
And back in the Koch building and also the Teague building, y'all did not take breaks mid-morning and mid-afternoon, did you?
And walk over to the MSC or anything like that?
No, we never got out of the building until quitting time.
But I do remember we used to go on Friday together, we would go
It was in the Coke building.
It was with Peggy Anderson and some others I remember.
It was the Coke building.
We used to go to the Texan for lunch, which we would get, for a dollar and a quarter, we got chicken fried steak, mashed potatoes, and a salad.
And it was the Texan, the one that...
It was the drive-in then.
It was a restaurant.
We ate inside in the restaurant.
Now, as a sidelight, during that era, where were the classiest places to eat in Bryan College Station?
I don't think we had any.
Let's see if I can remember the name.
The Captain's, there was a restaurant called the Captain's Table.
And of course, always the Mexican food places.
I'd have to really think about that.
Another example of how times change, where did you park as an employee?
Well, in the Koch building, I had my own reserve parking place.
Eventually, I graduated to that.
Immediately next door?
Immediately next door, and it was lovely, just lovely.
And then we moved to the Teague building.
We had to park across the street in Lot 55, which was okay.
But I did miss that.
adjacent parking.
It was nice.
I loved looking out at my window in the Koch Building onto Military Walk.
Because I have really pleasant memories of when my mother and I used to come out and park and watch the students march down Military Walk from Guyon Hall to Sevesa through there.
Describe the attitude of the students in general and what this campus was like in the 60s.
I had no problem.
We didn't see that many students.
Now remember, we didn't see the colleges pretty much, and we worked through their advisors and their deans.
So as far as interaction with students, except in the summer when we worked with registration, when we had to approve all the graduate registrations in the summer,
we didn't really get into the students' activities.
But were students polite?
Yes, it was their dress that was always so entertaining, so to speak, because they were various forms of dress and undress during the summer.
In those years, they were wearing the low-cut jeans and the hairdos and really some
Interesting thing, and we enjoyed that.
But were there ever any student troubles?
No, there were not.
And people from Washington would visit the campus, for instance, with Dr. Kunze, and they would just remark what a quiet, well-behaved student body.
There were no outrageous-looking people.
It was...
they were just impressed with the way it was performing at that time because they were having so many problems in other colleges.
And was the graduate college growing?
The graduate college was growing and growing and growing and Dr. Kunze fortunately had the foresight to go to the automated graduate student record system of which he
And the data processing center worked out a program which saved us in the long run, because we could never have handled all those records without it.
It was very popular.
He traveled over the countryside, especially to the colleges of the Council of Graduate Schools, and gave talks on that program.
I don't know how many of them adopted it, but they did visit to see what we were doing, how we were doing it.
Quite a breakthrough.
Did you and your friends think that A&M was making progress during those years?
Were we getting better and bigger?
Yes, because I would see the correspondents coming in from other schools and deans and places he visited saying the nice things about our programs and with great respect.
So I really realized we were getting bigger, and I was most proud of it.
Now, President Rutter's office was moved from the Koch Building to the System Building.
Yes.
Well, actually, they were in the Teague Building.
No, no, I know this before, before, while Rutter was still president.
He was in the System Building, wasn't he?
Yes.
From the System Building, I guess they moved to the Teague Building and then to the Koch Building.
Because we, we got their offices
in the Teague building, the president's office in the Teague building when we moved there.
They had been there and they wanted back in the Koch building.
Yeah.
So you weren't aware that Mr. Rutter's health was failing?
No.
In the late, or?
I wasn't, no.
I'm not sure whether.
Do you remember the reaction of the campus when Mr. Rutter died?
Oh, yes.
It was a shock to all of us.
We felt it.
Did you go to the memorial?
I did.
I went to the memorial.
I went to, um, what do you call it?
What the students, the ceremony the students.
Oh, oh, I mean, uh, uh, uh, Silver Taps.
Yeah.
Silver Taps.
Yes, yes.
Um, but we all did.
We all participated, and it was, um,
And Nelda was so, she was so,
